    teachingBody:
      "Integration is not the suppression of appetite or the silencing of spirit. It is the alignment of all three around a single direction. Appetite still hungers; spirit still has fire; reason still chooses — but they are no longer pulling against each other. The man feels singular, not because he is simple, but because he is governed.\n\nThe undivided man is not without desire. He has plenty of desire — perhaps more than the divided man, because his desire is not constantly being canceled by an opposing impulse. The difference is that his desire moves toward what he has chosen rather than wherever the loudest part is shouting.\n\nThis is the inner throne occupied. Not by tyranny — the throne is held lightly — but reliably. The kingdom knows where it is going. Every part has its work. The man can finally rest in his own command.",
