      "The small kingdom is the territory immediately under the man's command: his room, his desk, his schedule, his speech, his body, his immediate hours. It is the only kingdom most men will ever govern. It is also the kingdom on which everything larger depends.\n\nA man who cannot make his bed cannot reliably govern anything larger. Not because making the bed is morally significant, but because the discipline of ordering the small space is the same discipline as ordering the large life. Self-rule begins concretely, in the spaces the man actually inhabits, or it does not begin at all.\n\nThe King attends to the small kingdom not because it is glamorous but because it is real. The fantasy of governing a great enterprise while leaving the immediate territory chaotic is a fantasy. The Sovereign begins with what is under his hand and extends from there.",
