    id: 'day-53', dayNumber: 53, arcNumber: 6, arcTitle: 'The Forge',
    title: 'Make Something Real', theme: 'craft, production, thirty-minute rule',
    season: 'transmutation', archetype: 'craftsman',
    invocation: 'Today you walk as the Craftsman: a man who crosses from intending to making, with hands genuinely engaged.',
    archetypeExpression:
      "The Craftsman governs today because the made thing teaches and the plan does not — and his temptation is to hide in dignified preparation. He values realness over polish: the imperfect paragraph, the sketch no one sees, finished in thirty unbroken minutes. Today's command — making something real, smallness allowed — is the Craftsman letting the act of making change the man who makes it.",
    lineagePassageId: 'dhammapada-145-fashion',
    openingLine: 'Not planning to make. Making.',
    teachingBody:
      "Most men spend more time planning what they will build than building. The plan is dignified; it feels productive. But the plan returns nothing. Only the made thing — however small, however imperfect — returns something to the man. The made thing teaches him. The plan does not.\n\nThe thirty-minute rule: thirty minutes of actual making, with hands or mind genuinely engaged, beats two hours of planning. The piece of writing does not need to be good. The drawing does not need to be shown. The code does not need to ship. The exercise of making — beginning, struggling, completing or stopping at a real point — is itself the transmutation.\n\nThe Craftsman knows the secret most planners do not: the act of making changes the man making it. The plan changes nothing.",
    secretContentType: 'forge_assignment', secretTitle: 'Forge Assignment',
    secretBody: "Assignment: today, make one real thing in thirty unbroken minutes. Not the perfect thing. Not the impressive thing. The next clear thing in front of you. A paragraph. A sketch. A page of code. A meal cooked from scratch. A small piece of furniture repaired. What matters is that you crossed from intending to making, with no audience and no expectation. Record what you made. Tomorrow, make one more.",
    crownFragment: 'The made thing teaches. The plan only delays.',
    command: 'Today, make something real. The smallness is fine. The realness is the point.',
    practice: 'Thirty minutes of actual production, hands or mind engaged, no planning.',
    forgeChallenge: 'Finish one made thing today that has been in planning for too long.',
    journalPrompt: 'What plans am I confusing with progress? What would it look like to skip the planning and just make?',
