    id: 'day-54', dayNumber: 54, arcNumber: 6, arcTitle: 'The Forge',
    title: 'Craft Over Consumption', theme: 'creation vs consumption, energy direction',
    season: 'transmutation', archetype: 'craftsman',
    invocation: 'Today you walk as the Craftsman: a man who watches the ratio of what he consumes against what he makes.',
    archetypeExpression:
      "The Craftsman governs today because making builds the interior that consumption quietly thins — and his temptation is to absorb tools and content instead of building with them. He does not hate leisure; he keeps it small, chosen, in its place. Today's command — shifting one hour from consumption into the Forge — is the Craftsman remembering what the made thing returns that the consumed thing never does.",
    lineagePassageId: 'dhammapada-145-fashion',
    openingLine: 'Every hour of consumption is an hour not forging.',
    teachingBody:
      "The modern man is offered an enormous menu of consumption: media, content, entertainment, sports as spectacle, news as drama, scrolling as recreation. Each is engineered to be slightly more rewarding than the alternative, which is making something real. Each, taken at scale, leaves the man slightly emptier than he started.\n\nThis is not a moral judgment about leisure. Rest is real. Some consumption is genuinely restorative. But the ratio matters. A man who consumes ten hours for every one hour of making cannot be surprised when his interior feels thin. The Forge is where interiority is built. Consumption can be a small part of a full life. It cannot be the substance.\n\nThe Craftsman watches the ratio. He notices when consumption begins to fill what should be making. He shifts the balance — not by hating consumption, but by remembering what the made thing returns that the consumed thing does not.",
    secretContentType: 'archetype_trial', secretTitle: "The Craftsman's Trial",
    secretBody: "Trial: for one day, track the ratio honestly. How many minutes of consumption — phone, video, scrolling, passive watching? How many minutes of making — training, building, writing, studying, cooking, repairing? Do not judge. Just count. Then ask: is this the ratio of the man I am building? The Craftsman does not eliminate consumption. He keeps it in its place — small, occasional, chosen rather than defaulted to.",
    crownFragment: 'Consume less than you make. The man is the residue.',
