    id: 'day-55', dayNumber: 55, arcNumber: 6, arcTitle: 'The Forge',
    title: 'Study Burns Fog', theme: 'learning as Forge act, mind category',
    season: 'transmutation', archetype: 'sage',
    invocation: 'Today you walk as the Sage: a man who gives the fire to serious study and watches the fog of his interior lift.',
    archetypeExpression:
      "The Sage governs today because study is one of his worthiest Forge acts — not consumption of content, but slow work that gives the mind real labor and changes the man who does it. He reads to be changed, knowing a foggy mind is the compulsion's favorite terrain. Today's command — one real piece of study — is the Sage sharpening the instrument the whole practice depends on.",
    lineagePassageId: 'dhammapada-1-thought',
    openingLine: 'The fire enters the mind through serious study.',
    teachingBody:
      "Study is one of the most underrated Forge categories. Not consumption of content — that is something else — but serious, slow study of something worth understanding. A real book, read with attention. A skill, drilled with patience. A subject, returned to repeatedly until it begins to live in the mind.\n\nThe man who studies seriously finds the fog of his interior lifts. Not because he becomes encyclopedic, but because his mind has been given real work and has done it. The compulsion thrives on a foggy mind. Clear minds are less seducible. Study sharpens the instrument the practice depends on.\n\nThe Sage Forge act is not about credentials. It is about giving the fire one of its most worthy directions: into the mind, deliberately, with patience, returning the man each time slightly more capable of seeing what is in front of him.",
    secretContentType: 'hidden_teaching', secretTitle: 'Hidden Teaching',
    secretBody: "The classical philosophical schools — Stoic, Epicurean, Platonic — were not lecture halls. They were forms of life. Students lived together, practiced together, and studied together not to pass exams but to become a different kind of person. Study was a Forge. The reading was not separate from the practice. Modern men have lost this distinction; they read for information and wonder why nothing changes. Read to be changed. Study is a furnace if you let it be one.",
