      "There is work done from depletion and there is work done from a furnace. Both produce output. They are not the same work. The work done from a furnace has clarity, force, and a kind of weight the depleted work cannot match. The maker is fully in it. The product carries that.\n\nThe practice teaches a man to bring the conserved fire into his work. Not to be intense — intensity for its own sake is exhausting and unproductive — but to be present, awake, fully there. The compulsion thrives on a half-present worker. The forged worker is harder to derail.\n\nThe Builder's discipline is to let the work be the place the fire goes. Not the most glamorous work. The actual work in front of him today. Bring the fire there. The work will tell you what it does with it.",
