      "Prayer is a complicated word in modern usage. Here it is meant broadly: any practice of deliberate inner attention turned toward something larger than the self. It may be religious; it may be contemplative; it may be silent sitting; it may be a written morning offering. The form is less important than the function: a chosen, regular practice in which the man is not the center.\n\nThe man who pours conserved energy into this kind of attention finds it transforms in a particular way: it becomes quieter, deeper, less reactive. The compulsion thrives on reactivity. The contemplative man is more difficult terrain for it. He has practiced being still.\n\nThe Monk's Forge act is not piety. It is a deliberate, daily exposure of the inner life to something stable, beyond mood. The fire poured here returns as depth.",
