    teachingBody:
      "Service is the strangest of the Forge categories because it appears to spend the energy outward and returns it inward larger. The man who genuinely helps someone — not as performance, not for credit, simply as service — finds that the act has reorganized him. He is steadier. The compulsion has less room because something larger has occupied the space.\n\nThis is not sentimental. It is a structural feature of the human nervous system: meaningful service to another person quiets the self-referential loops that feed compulsive behavior. The man absorbed in his own urge cycle has very little capacity for genuine service. The man absorbed in genuine service has very little spare attention for the urge cycle.\n\nThe Brother's Forge act is to find one place today where the fire can go into someone else's need. The act does not need to be large. It needs to be real.",
